## Non-Blocking Servo Motor Controller

## Overview

This project controls a servo motor using an Arduino Uno.  
The controller supports automatic and manual operating modes.

The servo position is updated using non-blocking timing with `millis()`,
so the Arduino can perform other tasks while the servo is moving.

## Hardware

- Arduino Uno
- Servo motor
- Jumper wires

## Circuit Connection

| Servo connection | Arduino Uno |
|---|---|
| Signal | Digital pin 3 |
| VCC | 5V |
| GND | GND |

## Operating Modes

### Automatic mode

The servo automatically moves between predefined positions.

### Manual mode

The servo position can be controlled using commands entered through the
Arduino Serial Monitor.

## Serial Commands

| Command | Function |
|---|---|
| `a` | Select automatic mode |
| `m` | Select manual mode |

Add any additional angle-control commands used by the actual program.

## Technical Features

- Arduino Servo library
- Non-blocking timing using `millis()`
- Automatic and manual operating modes
- Servo angle validation
- Controller status through the Serial Monitor
- State-based control structure

## How to Run

1. Connect the servo signal wire to Arduino digital pin 3.
2. Connect the servo red wire to 5V.
3. Connect the servo ground wire to GND.
4. Open `Controlling_Servo_Motor.ino` in Arduino IDE.
5. Select Arduino Uno from the board menu.
6. Compile and upload the program.
7. Open the Serial Monitor.
8. Use the available commands to change the operating mode.

## Simulation Result

The servo motor successfully receives commands from the Arduino Uno and
moves its horn to the requested angle.

